Step-by-Step: Send Custom Metrics using CloudWatch Agent
________________________________________
üîπ Step : IAM Role with CloudWatch Permissions
If you're using an EC2 instance:
üëâ Create IAM Role:
1.	Go to IAM ‚Üí Roles ‚Üí Create role
2.	Select "EC2" as trusted entity
3.	Attach the following policies:
o	CloudWatchAgentServerPolicy
4.	Name it: e.g., EC2CloudWatchAgentRole
5.	Attach this role to your EC2 instance
Step 1: Download the .deb package manually (CloudWatch-Agent) (DOWNLOAD)

wget https://s3.amazonaws.com/amazoncloudwatch-agent/ubuntu/amd64/latest/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.deb
üîπ Step 2: Install the package (CloudWatch-Agent) (INSTALL)
 dpkg -i amazon-cloudwatch-agent.deb

CloudWatch Agent configuration is  now targeting:

‚úÖ Metrics Collection:
‚Ä¢	CPU (cpu_usage_idle, user, system)
‚Ä¢	Memory (mem_used_percent)
‚Ä¢	Disk usage for / (used_percent)
‚Ä¢	Namespace: CustomEC2Metrics
‚úÖ Logs Collection: (Nginx should be installed on your EC2 instance)
‚Ä¢	/var/log/nginx/access.log ‚Üí NGINXAccessLogs
‚Ä¢	/var/log/nginx/error.log ‚Üí NGINXErrorLogs




CloudWatch Agent Configuration File (JSON)  (CONFIGURE)
[]# vim config.json 
inside config.json paste below json file
{
  "agent": {
    "metrics_collection_interval": 60,
    "logfile": "/opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/logs/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.log",
    "run_as_user": "root"
  },
  "metrics": {
    "namespace": "CustomEC2Metrics",
    "append_dimensions": {
      "InstanceId": "${aws:InstanceId}"
    },
    "metrics_collected": {
      "cpu": {
        "measurement": [
          "cpu_usage_idle",
          "cpu_usage_user",
          "cpu_usage_system"
        ],
        "metrics_collection_interval": 60,
        "totalcpu": true
      },
      "mem": {
        "measurement": [
          "mem_used_percent"
        ],
        "metrics_collection_interval": 60
      },
      "disk": {
        "measurement": [
          "used_percent"
        ],
        "resources": [
          "/"
        ],
        "metrics_collection_interval": 60
      }
    }
  },
  "logs": {
    "logs_collected": {
      "files": {
        "collect_list": [
          {
            "file_path": "/var/log/nginx/access.log",
            "log_group_name": "NGINXAccessLogs",
            "log_stream_name": "{instance_id}-access",
            "timestamp_format": "%d/%b/%Y:%H:%M:%S"
          },
          {
            "file_path": "/var/log/nginx/error.log",
            "log_group_name": "NGINXErrorLogs",
            "log_stream_name": "{instance_id}-error",
            "timestamp_format": "%Y/%m/%d %H:%M:%S"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}


‚ñ∂Ô∏è Start CloudWatch Agent with This Config (RUN)

 /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/bin/amazon-cloudwatch-agent-ctl \
-a fetch-config \
-m ec2 \
-c file:config.json \
-s


Verify:
View Custom Metrics in CloudWatch
1.	Go to CloudWatch Console
https://console.aws.amazon.com/cloudwatch
2.	Click "Metrics" in the left menu.
3.	Click "All metrics" ‚Üí Select CustomEC2Metrics.
4.	Choose "InstanceId" to view metrics.
5.	View metrics like:
o	mem_used_percent
o	disk_used_percent
o	cpu_usage_idle, cpu_usage_user, cpu_usage_system
View Logs in CloudWatch
1.	Go to CloudWatch Console
https://console.aws.amazon.com/cloudwatch
2.	In the left menu, click ‚ÄúLogs‚Äù ‚Üí ‚ÄúLog groups‚Äù.
3.	Find your log groups:
o	NGINXAccessLogs
o	NGINXErrorLogs

üî∏ On EC2 instance:

tail -f /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/logs/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.log

agent status check
 []# systemctl status amazon-cloudwatch-agent


